## Story 4 — Return-to-Sender Exit

**Description:** Shipment cannot be routed, Ray decides to return it to sender (RTS) → workflow closes completely.

**Actors:** Ray (Supervisor) · Conductor

### Flow

```
SHP-44952: Through 2 sort sessions, still unrouted
  → Ray: Decision — Return to Sender
  → Ray: Initiate RTS resolution for SHP-44952
  → Conductor: Cancel Routing Task
  → 📤 Workflow CLOSED — RTS terminal state
     Chain of custody: scanned → collected → RTS decision
  → [Future] RTS Workflow (not yet built — manual process currently)
```

### Comparison of 3 terminal states

| Terminal State | Trigger | Outcome |
|---|---|---|
| ✅ Re-sorted | Routing done, sorted to correct position | Workflow complete. Shipment loaded onto vehicle. |
| 🏪 Storage | Ray defers — routing task cancelled | Shipment into problem-solve area. Next shift continues. |
| 📤 RTS | Ray decides to return to client | Workflow closed. Handoff to RTS process. |

> 💡 **Key insight:** RTS is the *exit signal* of the no-route workflow. Conductor has fulfilled its obligation: scan → collect → decision. The physical return process will be a separate Conductor workflow in the future.

