## Story 7 — Misplaced Shipment After Pallet Move

**Description:** Marco moves pallet, one shipment falls to the floor. System detects a gap in expected scans and alerts Ray.

**Actors:** Marco (Runner) · Carlos (Induction) · Ray (Supervisor) · Conductor

### Flow

```
Marco: Move PLT-2200 to induction [18 shipments on pallet]
  → Conductor: PLT-2200 "consumed by sort session" [Expects 18 scans]
  → Carlos: Scans 17/18 shipments off pallet [SHP-45107 — no scan recorded]
  → Conductor: ⚠️ Flag SHP-45107 as "potentially misplaced"
  → Ray: Dashboard alert — 1 shipment missing from PLT-2200
  → Ray: Check movement history [inducted 5:22 → collected 5:23 → onto pallet 5:40]
  → Ray: Directs Marco to retrace PLT-2200's path
  → Marco: Finds SHP-45107 on the floor, 10 feet from induction
  → Carlos: Scan shipment → label → belt
  → ✅ Misplaced flag cleared [SHP-45107 re-enters sort flow normally]
```

### Chain of Custody — SHP-45107

| Time | Event |
|---|---|
| 5:22 PM | Inducted (Carlos) |
| 5:23 PM | Collected (Ana) |
| 5:40 PM | Onto PLT-2200 |
| 6:45 PM | ⚠️ Fell off pallet |
| 7:05 PM | ✅ Found → re-scanned |

> 💡 **Key insight:** Conductor knows PLT-2200 has 18 shipments. When the pallet is "consumed", the system *expects* 18 scans. Gap = alert. The system never loses track of an obligation — even when the package is on the floor.

